19:38.611 --> 19:39.545 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Committee, we thank you.

19:39.578 --> 19:40.546 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

19:40.579 --> 19:46.185 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TODD ROKITA: Thank you, Judy.

19:46.218 --> 19:55.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Another piece of
the Trump
agenda is getting attention
today, and that

19:55.494 --> 20:00.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is the president's revised
travel ban, which
hit a roadblock in the federal
courts.

20:00.433 --> 20:02.368 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan has more.

20:02.401 --> 20:07.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The first
ruling came yesterday
in Hawaii, where a federal judge
blocked parts

20:07.106 --> 20:08.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the executive order.

20:08.908 --> 20:13.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It would have barred refugees,
as well as
nationals from six
Muslim-majority countries,

20:13.245 --> 20:15.081 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from entering the U.S.

20:15.114 --> 20:19.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, overnight, a federal judge
in Maryland
issued his own block on the
six-nation travel

20:19.118 --> 20:20.886 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ban.

20:20.920 --> 20:23.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on all this, we turn to
Devlin Barrett,
who now covers the Justice
Department and

20:23.089 --> 20:25.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
national security issues for The
Washington
Post.

20:25.324 --> 20:29.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Devlin, this was supposed to
be the executive
order designed to skirt around
the legal challenges

20:29.829 --> 20:30.796 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that the first one had.

20:30.830 --> 20:32.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What were the problems?

20:32.665 --> 20:35.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DEVLIN BARRETT, The Washington
Post: Well,
the first one basically
foundered on due process

20:35.968 --> 20:37.736 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
problems.

20:37.770 --> 20:40.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Basically, the federal appeals
court ruled
that the order had not been
written to give

20:40.973 --> 20:45.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people a fair shake in the
system essentially,
particularly people who had
visas or green

20:45.478 --> 20:46.879 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
cards.

20:46.912 --> 20:48.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So they changed that part of it,
and they
thought they fixed that problem.

20:49.014 --> 20:50.783 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And, in a sense, they had.

20:50.816 --> 20:55.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what you saw in the last two
rulings by
federal judges is that now
there's a conflict

20:55.554 --> 21:01.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
over the real meat of the
argument, which
is, is this a Muslim ban or some
partial version

21:01.827 --> 21:03.596 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of a Muslim ban?

21:03.629 --> 21:08.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what both these judges came
down on as
saying that, yes, it was
essentially a violation

21:08.467 --> 21:12.872 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of the First Amendment rule that
you can't
disfavor a particular religion.

21:12.905 --> 21:17.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There aren't
any explicit
terms directly in the new
executive order

21:17.543 --> 21:19.512 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that say Muslim or Islam.

21:19.545 --> 21:24.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It seems that the Hawaii ruling
seems to take
a lot of candidate Trump's words
and the administration's

21:24.283 --> 21:25.885 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
words and put them in there.

21:25.918 --> 21:27.686 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DEVLIN BARRETT: Well, right.

21:27.720 --> 21:33.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Trump administration has
really struggled
in the legal process to separate
itself from

21:33.425 --> 21:37.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what the campaign has said, what
the president
has said, and even what some of
his top advisers

21:37.796 --> 21:40.332 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have said in defending the
order.

21:40.366 --> 21:45.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those statements have all
been thrown
back at them by the judges, and
it's really,

21:45.337 --> 21:51.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
frankly, remarkable the extent
to which the
travel ban, both versions of it,
have been

21:51.310 --> 21:56.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tossed at this point, or at
least suspended
at this point, based on the
words of the president

21:56.282 --> 21:57.650 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and his senior advisers.

21:57.683 --> 21:59.685 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Well, what is
the Justice
Department going to do?

21:59.718 --> 22:03.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DEVLIN BARRETT: Well, every
indication is
that they are going to appeal
this.

22:03.155 --> 22:07.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Appeals -- notices of appeals
could come as
soon as tonight in the two new
rulings.

22:07.626 --> 22:11.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a third case where
everyone is just
sort of waiting to see how the
judge exactly

22:11.630 --> 22:13.265 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
handles that.

22:13.299 --> 22:16.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the expectation is there
will be more
appeals over this, more fights
over it.

22:16.435 --> 22:22.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, frankly, I think, this set
of legal challenges
will really be an argument about
the basic

22:22.441 --> 22:28.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
issue of the term Muslim ban,
and is that
an accurate description of what
this executive

22:28.380 --> 22:30.149 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
order does?

22:30.182 --> 22:32.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But what's the
likelihood
then that this executive order
gets challenged

22:32.284 --> 22:37.356 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
perhaps in other federal
districts, other
regions and has to be
reconciled?

22:37.389 --> 22:39.525 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DEVLIN BARRETT: Well, it's
growing every day.

22:39.558 --> 22:45.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for example, last night, we
saw two different
parts of the country in which
federal judges

22:45.698 --> 22:47.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ruled on it.

22:47.633 --> 22:51.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That means that, assuming the
appeals go through,
you will see appeals courts
ruling in one

22:51.470 --> 22:55.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
part of the country and another
part of the
country, and oftentimes, just
the way the

22:55.574 --> 22:58.711 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
court system works, those
rulings don't match
up identically.

22:58.744 --> 23:03.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when that happens, it
increases the likelihood
that something will go to the
Supreme Court.

23:03.349 --> 23:07.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That all depends, of course, on
the notion
that both sides still want to
fight, but every

23:07.620 --> 23:11.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
indication right now is that
whoever wins
or loses at the appeals court
round, the other

23:12.024 --> 23:13.692 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
side will want to keep fighting.

23:13.726 --> 23:17.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Devlin Barrett
of The Washington Post, thanks
so much.

23:18.030 --> 23:24.870 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DEVLIN BARRETT: Sure.

23:24.903 --> 23:30.309 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

23:30.342 --> 23:36.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
