world.

23:40.819 --> 23:46.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: German Chancellor
Angela Merkel
has her first meeting with
President Trump

23:46.325 --> 23:47.826 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
tomorrow at the White House.

23:47.860 --> 23:51.130 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Mrs. Merkel is seeking
reelection later this
year.

23:51.163 --> 23:56.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tops on the agenda for the two
leaders: the
NATO response to a resurgent
Russia and the

23:56.235 --> 23:59.204 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
stability of the European Union
after Brexit.

23:59.238 --> 24:04.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I sat down with Germany's
ambassador to the
U.S., Peter Wittig, and I asked
him about

24:04.410 --> 24:06.545 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the importance of this
high-stakes meeting.

24:06.578 --> 24:09.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG, German Ambassador
to the United
States: Well, it is an important
visit for

24:09.715 --> 24:11.317 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
her.

24:11.350 --> 24:14.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's her first personal
encounter with
a new president.

24:14.720 --> 24:17.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have spoken on the phone a
couple of
times.

24:17.423 --> 24:21.827 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But personal relationships are
important.

24:21.860 --> 24:29.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for us, Judy, the U.S. has
been almost
the most important international
and foreign

24:29.802 --> 24:31.837 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
policy partner over decades.

24:31.870 --> 24:37.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. has helped us to build
a thriving
democracy after the Second World
War.

24:37.676 --> 24:40.412 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It has helped us to unify
Germany.

24:40.446 --> 24:48.520 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, that's a very strong
tradition, a strong
basis on which the chancellor
will build on

24:48.554 --> 24:54.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and establish constructive and
forward-looking
relations with this new
president in the U.S.

24:54.460 --> 24:56.228 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well -- excuse
me.

24:56.261 --> 25:01.367 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We know NATO is a subject that
has come up
repeatedly during Mr. Trump's
campaign for

25:01.400 --> 25:02.434 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
president.

25:02.468 --> 25:03.769 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He's been critical of NATO.

25:03.802 --> 25:07.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's said that the U.S. pays far
more into
NATO than it should.

25:07.172 --> 25:10.609 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's leaned on other NATO
members to pay more.

25:10.642 --> 25:14.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How much more is the chancellor
willing to
say Germany will pay, and by
when?

25:14.380 --> 25:18.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: NATO is the
bedrock of our common
security.

25:18.150 --> 25:27.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was kind of reinvigorated
after Russian
invaded Ukraine and fueled the
conflict in

25:27.459 --> 25:29.194 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Eastern Ukraine.

25:29.228 --> 25:37.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it is on a new mission
against a newly
assertive Russia and facing
challenges in

25:37.403 --> 25:41.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the south of the NATO territory,
in the Middle
East, for instance.

25:41.707 --> 25:46.078 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But there is this discussion on
fairer burden-sharing.

25:46.111 --> 25:48.213 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We're ready for this discussion.

25:48.247 --> 25:50.949 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's an important discussion.

25:50.983 --> 25:59.425 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Germany is committed to do more
for the defense,
to increase our defense spending
incrementally.

25:59.458 --> 26:03.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Last year, for instance, we
raised our defense
budget by 9 percent.

26:03.429 --> 26:09.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we want to go forward on
this path in
an incremental way.

26:09.368 --> 26:16.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yes, Europe, and also Germany
have to be more
active in defense.

26:16.708 --> 26:20.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You mentioned a
more aggressive
Russia.

26:20.312 --> 26:26.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We know President Trump has
spoken about the
suggestion that he would take a
more conciliatory

26:26.418 --> 26:27.953 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
approach to Russia.

26:27.986 --> 26:32.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If that's what this president
does, what will
Chancellor Merkel's response be?

26:32.157 --> 26:36.895 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: She has a lot of
experience
in dealing with Russia.

26:36.929 --> 26:42.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She has spoken so many times
with President
Putin over the last years.

26:42.267 --> 26:48.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think we are pursuing a
double-track approach,
strong dialogue, keeping the
channels of communication

26:48.807 --> 26:57.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
open, but, at the same time,
being very resolute
about our defense, keeping in
mind our security

26:57.282 --> 27:01.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
interests, especially in the
eastern part
of Europe and beyond.

27:01.153 --> 27:09.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think we would welcome a
new chapter
of the American and Russian
leader in their

27:09.228 --> 27:15.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
relationships, but on the basis
of a very
clear idea where our strategic
interests and

27:15.367 --> 27:16.768 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
our security interests are.

27:16.802 --> 27:18.670 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You expect that
to come up?

27:18.704 --> 27:25.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: I could assume
that they will
be talking about Russia and the
Ukraine conflict,

27:26.011 --> 27:27.279 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
about many other things, Judy.

27:27.312 --> 27:29.414 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We spoke about
NATO.

27:29.448 --> 27:32.150 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The president has also been
critical of the
European Union.

27:32.184 --> 27:38.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was one of the first to argue
that Great
Britain should leave the E.U.,
so-called Brexit.

27:38.657 --> 27:42.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is Chancellor Merkel's plan
to change
his mind on the E.U.?

27:42.227 --> 27:44.196 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: Europe is our
home.

27:44.229 --> 27:46.265 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's our neighborhood.

27:46.298 --> 27:51.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We are strong supporters of a
strong and resilient
European Union.

27:51.937 --> 27:54.439 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We deplore Brexit.

27:54.473 --> 27:57.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We respect the vote of the
people.

27:57.943 --> 28:05.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We want to have close relations
with the U.K.
even after they left the
European Union.

28:05.651 --> 28:12.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we will do everything to
keep the European
Union as a strong and resilient
economic and

28:12.491 --> 28:13.992 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
political union.

28:14.026 --> 28:15.827 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And let me add this.

28:15.861 --> 28:21.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it is also in the
strategic interests
of the United States to have a
strong and

28:21.934 --> 28:28.073 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
resilient Europe, European
Union, in the face
of the challenges from the east
and from the

28:28.106 --> 28:30.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
south of our continent in
Europe.

28:30.075 --> 28:33.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And one can
presume those are
arguments the chancellor is
going to make

28:33.946 --> 28:34.980 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to the president?

28:35.013 --> 28:36.481 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: I assume so.

28:36.515 --> 28:38.216 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

28:38.250 --> 28:40.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally, I have
to ask you
about some of the comments
President Trump

28:40.752 --> 28:46.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
made about the chancellor
herself last year
with regard to her refugee
policy.

28:46.191 --> 28:50.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He called it, among other
things, "a sad shame
and a disgrace."

28:50.462 --> 28:55.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He went so far to say last year
-- and I'm
quoting -- he said: "The German
people are

28:55.667 --> 28:58.403 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to end up overthrowing
this woman.

28:58.437 --> 29:02.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't know what the hell she
is thinking,"
he wrote.

29:02.274 --> 29:05.010 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Does she believe she has
President Trump's
respect?

29:05.043 --> 29:10.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: You know, the
situation two
years ago, when the refugee
crisis emerged,

29:10.349 --> 29:11.883 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
was totally extraordinary.

29:11.917 --> 29:18.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was the biggest, largest
movement of people
since the Second World War.

29:18.323 --> 29:23.895 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it was an extraordinary
humanitarian crisis
at our borders.

29:23.929 --> 29:25.998 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Now the situation is different.

29:26.031 --> 29:29.001 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The numbers are dramatically
down.

29:29.034 --> 29:34.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The refugees that came in are
properly registered
and vetted.

29:34.806 --> 29:38.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we have gone back to an
orderly and regular
process.

29:38.410 --> 29:41.613 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, the situation has changed
since that time.

29:41.647 --> 29:46.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what about
the comments
that the president made about
her and her

29:46.151 --> 29:47.219 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
policy?

29:47.252 --> 29:49.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can she just -- does she think
he has his
respect?

29:49.287 --> 29:56.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: The chancellor, I
think, is
interested to build a strong,
constructive,

29:56.128 --> 30:00.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
forward-looking relationship
with President
Trump.

30:00.065 --> 30:09.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And she has said many times she
will not go
back to the campaign, but will
want to engage

30:09.074 --> 30:11.276 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with him in a constructive
manner.

30:11.309 --> 30:13.745 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think that's what we want
to see tomorrow.

30:13.779 --> 30:16.682 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, we will be
watching tomorrow's
visit.

30:16.715 --> 30:24.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Germany's Ambassador to the
United States
Peter Wittig, thank you very
much.

30:24.189 --> 30:29.661 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PETER WITTIG: Thank you, Judy.

30:29.695 --> 30:36.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We often hear
about and cover
the struggles that many
Americans face when

30:36.068 --> 30:37.903 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they try to land a good job.

30:37.936 --> 30:42.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you have a disability, the
challenge to
getting hired or even getting a
response to

30:42.841 --> 30:48.313 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
an inquiry, much less a
face-to-face interview,
is significantly harder.

30:48.346 --> 30:52.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our economics correspondent,
Paul Solman,
explores why that's still
happening.

30:52.951 --> 30:55.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of his weekly series,
Making Sense.

30:55.554 --> 30:57.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMI PROFETA, Job Seeker (through
computer):
Good evening.

30:57.889 --> 30:59.725 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
My name is Ami Profeta.

30:59.758 --> 31:03.361 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Ami Profeta has
cerebral palsy.

31:03.395 --> 31:05.664 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's been looking for work for
over a year.

31:05.697 --> 31:10.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMI PROFETA (through computer):
People have
hung up the phone.

31:10.168 --> 31:11.737 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They don't respond to my
e-mails.

31:11.770 --> 31:16.274 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Profeta's job hunt
may be more
challenging than most.

31:16.308 --> 31:22.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The unemployment rate for those
with a disability
is more than double the rate for
those without.

31:22.514 --> 31:25.717 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We interviewed economist Douglas
Kruse, himself
a paraplegic, via Skype.

31:25.751 --> 31:29.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DOUGLAS KRUSE, Rutgers
University: It's not
just a matter of people with
disabilities,

31:29.421 --> 31:32.824 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you know, staying at home and
collecting disability
income.

31:32.858 --> 31:38.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a matter of people who want
to work are
not as easily able to find work.

31:38.597 --> 31:46.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: In a 2015 study,
Kruse's research
team submitted 6,000 fake online
job applications

31:46.037 --> 31:48.673 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for accounting positions.

31:48.707 --> 31:54.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One-third said the applicant had
a spinal
cord injury, another third
Asperger's syndrome.

31:54.546 --> 31:57.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And one-third didn't mention a
disability
at all.

31:57.916 --> 31:59.718 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
The results?

31:59.751 --> 32:04.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DOUGLAS KRUSE: People with
disabilities were
26 percent less likely to get
expressions

32:04.289 --> 32:05.624 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of employer interest.

32:05.657 --> 32:07.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: What's going on, do
you suppose?

32:07.659 --> 32:10.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DOUGLAS KRUSE: There's a lot of
discomfort
with people with disabilities.

32:10.962 --> 32:15.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, apart from that,
there's a lot of
uncertainty: Oh, geez, someone
with a spinal

32:15.734 --> 32:18.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cord injury, I'm not sure
they're going to
fit in here.

32:18.403 --> 32:21.139 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MASON AMERI, Rutgers University:
They refer
to it as fear of the unknown.

32:21.173 --> 32:23.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Mason Ameri
co-authored the study.

32:23.575 --> 32:26.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MASON AMERI: How do I know if
this person
can do the job?

32:26.178 --> 32:27.879 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How do I know the cost?

32:27.913 --> 32:33.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, all of these unknowns
ultimately compel
an employer to express no hiring
intent.

32:33.785 --> 32:38.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Even though the
Americans With
Disabilities Act bars such
discrimination

32:38.323 --> 32:42.394 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for firms with more than 15
employees.

32:42.427 --> 32:46.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nicole Ellis returned to the job
market after
the bank she worked at went
bust.

32:46.731 --> 32:52.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But she decided to leave off her
resume the
fact that she is legally blind
due to ocular

32:52.971 --> 32:54.639 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
albinism.

32:54.673 --> 32:55.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICOLE ELLIS, Liberty Resources:
I didn't
think that I would be able to
get my foot

32:55.574 --> 32:57.375 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the door.

32:57.409 --> 33:01.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: It still took
three-and-a-half
years to land a job here at
Liberty Resources,

33:01.413 --> 33:06.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a Philadelphia nonprofit which
promotes independent
living for the disabled.

33:06.251 --> 33:08.119 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICOLE ELLIS: I would get the
calls back.

33:08.153 --> 33:10.522 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I would go on the interviews.

33:10.555 --> 33:15.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And once you start discussing --
because I
have to let them know that I'm
going to need

33:15.994 --> 33:21.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these accommodations, like
software that enlarges
fonts or enhances speech
recognition.

33:21.833 --> 33:29.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, once you start talking about
those things,
it kind of becomes like dead
silence, almost.

33:29.407 --> 33:30.375 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
And they...

33:30.408 --> 33:31.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: Really?

33:31.409 --> 33:32.377 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You can feel it?

33:32.410 --> 33:34.212 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NICOLE ELLIS: You can feel it.

33:34.246 --> 33:39.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then they will give you some
other scenarios
as far as, well, what about,
let's say, if

33:39.417 --> 33:40.385 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it snows?

33:40.418 --> 33:42.888 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Are you going to be able to get
into work?

33:42.921 --> 33:48.026 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: But you can
understand, or can
you not understand why an
employer would be

33:48.059 --> 33:49.794 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
concerned about all those sorts
of things?

33:49.828 --> 33:57.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICOLE ELLIS: I do understand,
but, on the
other hand, I have worked around
people who

33:57.602 --> 34:03.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
do not have disabilities who do
not come to
work and who do not work.

34:03.375 --> 34:05.310 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

34:05.343 --> 34:09.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICOLE ELLIS: So, I mean, to me,
I understand
the doubt and the questions, but
you are discriminating

34:09.948 --> 34:13.351 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
just based on the what-ifs of
someone's disability.

34:13.385 --> 34:17.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Liam Dougherty has
a master's
in public administration from
the University

34:17.956 --> 34:23.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Pennsylvania, and ataxia, a
condition marked
by a lack of muscle
coordination.

34:23.194 --> 34:28.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LIAM DOUGHERTY, Liberty
Resources: The way
that disability affects --
affects employment

34:28.466 --> 34:31.937 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is more insidious, more subtle,
more insidious.

34:31.970 --> 34:34.306 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My resume has all these gaps in
there.

34:34.339 --> 34:40.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think an employer looks
at that,
and they see, you know, like why
has this

34:40.211 --> 34:42.080 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
guy not been working?

34:42.113 --> 34:47.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, the gaps in
your work history,
and the kinds of work you
haven't done, are

34:47.619 --> 34:49.087 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
kind of signals, you think?

34:49.120 --> 34:50.555 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LIAM DOUGHERTY: Definitely.

34:50.588 --> 34:54.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Dougherty, like
Ellis, also found
work here at Liberty.

34:54.993 --> 35:00.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Bill Krebs says employers have
always underestimated
him because of his intellectual
disability.

35:01.032 --> 35:03.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BILL KREBS, Liberty Resources:
MDNM /Suffers
From Disability: At one time, it
was the R-word.

35:03.068 --> 35:04.035 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We got rid of the R-word.

35:04.069 --> 35:05.270 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It means mentally retarded.

35:05.303 --> 35:08.673 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I was labeled with a mental
retardation.

35:08.707 --> 35:12.544 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My I.Q. is mild, so I was I.Q.
of 70.

35:12.577 --> 35:16.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When you're labeled with a
disability, it's
like Hitler did to the Jews.

35:16.181 --> 35:20.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They put a tattoo on your arm,
and that stigma
stays with you the rest of your
life.

35:20.251 --> 35:21.853 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: So, once you're
stigmatized,
then?

35:21.886 --> 35:22.954 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BILL KREBS: That's it.

35:22.988 --> 35:24.322 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: You're out of the
game?

35:24.356 --> 35:26.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BILL KREBS: You're out of the
game, no matter
how hard you try.

35:26.524 --> 35:32.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Until he too found
a niche at
Liberty, where disability is a
commonplace.

35:32.330 --> 35:38.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what prompted this story is
a second and
more surprising finding of the
Kruse-Ameri

35:38.103 --> 35:44.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
research: Early results show
that when they
sent applications just for jobs
in data entry

35:44.676 --> 35:46.311 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and software development...

35:46.344 --> 35:48.313 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MASON AMERI: We found no
evidence of discrimination.

35:48.346 --> 35:49.581 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PAUL SOLMAN: None?

35:49.614 --> 35:50.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MASON AMERI: None, at least not
with the preliminary
data.

35:51.016 --> 35:53.351 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And why might that
be?

35:53.385 --> 35:58.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We went looking for a case study
in the real
world, and found one in
Philadelphia at an

35:58.990 --> 36:00.191 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
accounting firm.

36:00.225 --> 36:02.193 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE HOWE, EY Americas: We make
a concerted
effort now.

36:02.227 --> 36:07.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're going to universities
speaking to the
people responsible for their
students with

36:07.599 --> 36:09.234 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
disabilities.

36:09.267 --> 36:16.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Steve Howe is
managing partner
for EY Americas, formerly Ernst
&amp; Young.

36:16.574 --> 36:22.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a pilot program, it's pushing
to hire more
people with autism, a group that
has had,

36:22.280 --> 36:29.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up until now, an estimated un-
and under-employment
rate of between 70 and 90
percent.

36:29.154 --> 36:30.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But, says Sam Briefer:

36:30.955 --> 36:36.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SAM BRIEFER, EY Americas: We all
bring something
to the table that a lot of
people cannot.

36:36.561 --> 36:39.197 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We are very detail-oriented.

36:39.230 --> 36:42.767 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We analyze things in a very
specific way.

36:42.801 --> 36:47.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Briefer is one of
four recent
hires here with autism spectrum
disorder.

36:47.572 --> 36:54.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SAM BRIEFER: There are others
that are very
more detail-oriented than --
than I am and

36:54.479 --> 36:55.780 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are much better with numbers.

36:55.814 --> 36:58.550 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Well, it's an
accounting firm.

36:58.583 --> 37:01.619 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I guess being good with numbers
is probably
a good thing.

37:01.653 --> 37:02.687 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SAM BRIEFER: It is.

37:02.720 --> 37:03.688 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
It is.

37:03.721 --> 37:05.490 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it puts us all at a huge
advantage.

37:05.523 --> 37:09.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But, of course,
people on the
spectrum typically have trouble
socializing,

37:09.561 --> 37:11.830 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
communicating, an obvious
handicap.

37:11.863 --> 37:14.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Were you nervous about taking
the job?

37:14.799 --> 37:16.701 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SAM BRIEFER: I was, yes.

37:16.734 --> 37:23.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I first thought that I would be
communicating
with a lot of people at once,
which is something

37:23.274 --> 37:25.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that I always get stressed
about.

37:25.677 --> 37:32.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But knowing that I'm -- I work
independently
a lot makes me feel a lot better
with where

37:32.517 --> 37:34.119 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
I work.

37:34.152 --> 37:37.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: When things do get
stressful,
EY brings in a job coach to
help.

37:37.922 --> 37:43.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The team's regular manager,
Jamell Mitchell,
got neurodiversity training
ahead of time,

37:43.528 --> 37:44.896 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but he's also learning on the
job.

37:44.929 --> 37:48.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMELL MITCHELL, EY Americas:
They're very
specific and very clear.

37:48.066 --> 37:55.740 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As opposed to possibly a
neurotypical person
that may try to slide in at
9:10, the folks

37:55.773 --> 37:59.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that are on the spectrum will
say, hey, I
arrived at 9:02 today.

37:59.310 --> 38:01.713 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Do I need to work until 6:02?

38:01.746 --> 38:04.082 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And your reaction
to that?

38:04.115 --> 38:06.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMELL MITCHELL: Don't worry
about the two
minutes.

38:06.151 --> 38:07.118 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We're OK.

38:07.152 --> 38:08.953 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

38:08.987 --> 38:10.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STAN HWANG, EY Americas: A lot
of people on
the spectrum tend to be, or at
least initially,

38:10.221 --> 38:13.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more -- more rigid in their --
in some of
their thinking.

38:13.158 --> 38:18.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But says program
participant
Stan Hwang, this form of
rigidity has a major

38:18.329 --> 38:19.797 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
upside.

38:19.831 --> 38:23.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STAN HWANG: It also tends to
make them want
to be more honest, I think.

38:23.701 --> 38:29.340 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What would be the point of,
like, lying about
something or being deceptive?

38:29.374 --> 38:32.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Because you're more
naturally
just straightforward?

38:32.677 --> 38:35.446 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STAN HWANG: Yes.

38:35.480 --> 38:41.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: Managing partner
Howe recently
gave the team behind the pilot
program a Better

38:41.386 --> 38:42.887 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Begins With You Award.

38:42.921 --> 38:44.789 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: Well, thank you very much.

38:44.822 --> 38:49.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: But, look, this
isn't about feel-good
inclusivity, so much as boosting
the bottom

38:49.661 --> 38:51.362 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
line.

38:51.396 --> 38:55.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Howe hopes to leverage the
special abilities
he's seen in his workers with
autism.

38:56.000 --> 39:03.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE HOWE: We have learned from
technology
companies like SAP, Microsoft,
HP, who have

39:03.474 --> 39:05.577 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hired people with these kind of
skills.

39:05.610 --> 39:11.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We think it's a rich talent
pool, and we're
going to expand this now from
this exercise

39:11.683 --> 39:16.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Philadelphia to three or four
other cities
in the next year, and scale this
up.

39:16.821 --> 39:21.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And that means more
job prospects
for people on the spectrum like
Stan Hwang.

39:21.693 --> 39:30.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STAN HWANG: No matter what kind
of functionality
a person may be, everyone wants
to be treated

39:30.034 --> 39:32.503 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
like a human being, and
everybody deserves
an opportunity.

39:32.537 --> 39:37.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SOLMAN: And, at long last,
in certain
jobs, they're getting one.

